{"cursor":"12422","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n\nFirestarter}}\n\n after arson on July 9, 2004.]] 'Arson' 'arson' 1680, from Anglo-French.\n arsoun (1275), from Old French arsion, from L.L. arsionem (nom. arsio) \"a\n burning,\" from L. arsus pp. of ardere \"to burn,\" from PIE base *as- \"to burn,\n glow\" (see ardent). The Old English term was bÃ¦rnet, lit. \"burning;\" and Coke\n has indictment of burning (1640). Arsonist is from 1864. Dictionary.com. Online\n Etymology Dictionary. Douglas Harper, Historian.\n [http://dictionary.reference.com/browse/arson] (accessed: January 27,\n 2008) is the crime of intentionally and maliciously setting fire to\n buildings, wildland areas, {{cite journal\n  | url = http://www.aic.gov.au/publications/tandi2/tandi350.html title =\n  | Deliberately lit vegetation fires in Australia journal = Trends and issues\n  | in crime and criminal justice issue = 350 isbn = 978-1-921185-71-7 issn =\n  | 0817-8542 publisher = Australian Institute of Criminology last = Kumar\n  | first = Kris pages = location = Lynnwood date = February 2008 accessdate =\n  | 2009-01-09\n|archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20080722133206/http://www.aic.gov.au/p-\nublications/tandi2/tandi350.html  |archivedate =\n2008-07-22}}  vehicles  or other property with the intent\nto cause damage. It may be distinguished from other causes such as spontaneous\ncombustion and natural wildfires. Arson often involves fires deliberately set to\nthe property of another or to one's own property as to collect insurance\ncompensation. [http://dictionary.reference.com/browse/arson 'arson'].\nDictionary.com. The American Heritage Dictionary of the English Language, Fourth\nEdition. Houghton Mifflin Company, 2004. Accessed: January 27, 2008)\n\nA person who commits this crime is called an 'arsonist'. Many arsonists use\naccelerants, such as gasoline or kerosene to get a fire going. ]]\n","linknr":348,"url":"Arson","recorded":1364040387,"links":["/w/inde